    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-10-08T18:36:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-10-08T18:36:00-05:00" n="893"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d893">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">318.115Un3/11: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at San José</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Chase</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San José</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-10-08T18:00:00-05:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 8, 1920—6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 9—10 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>70. Your number 21, August 17, 6 p.m. The reply of the Costa Rican
                        Government<note n="14" xml:id="d893fn14">Dated Oct. 5; not printed.</note>
                    has just been received alleging that subsoil rights always belonged to the
                    State. The communication is long. Particulars by mail today.<note n="15"
                        xml:id="d893fn15">Not printed.</note> I will send summary by cable if
                    desired.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Chase</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
